  - key: '[주-D001] 腹 : '
    value: 甁
english:
  title: Tea Brewed by Lamplight at Night
  author: Jeong Hee-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    How deep the night when snow threatens to fall,
    In this ancient house beneath the blue lamp, cold steals sleep.
    I fetch the old jar from the bedside, moss-grown and weathered,
    And pour the jade-green waters of a crystalline spring.

    I kindle the flame with perfect balance and measure,
    While moonlight shimmers on the wall and smoke curls gently.
    Pine wind whispers through the hollow valley,
    As waterfalls crash and thunder through the distant stream.
    Thunder rolls and lightning darts in their fury,
    Like swift wheels tumbling down the mountain pass—
    Then suddenly the clouds part and the wind subsides,
    Waves settle into stillness, clear and tranquil.

    I pour it forth in a gourd, and white light blooms like snow,
    My very liver and heart seem to pierce through heaven.
    Sipping slowly, I drill through the chaos of becoming,
    Riding the divine steed alone into the realm of beginning.

    Looking back at the scattered gravel of my former mind,
    Demons and worldly dust fade into oblivion.
    The wellspring of consciousness opens wide,
    And I wander free, transcending all things.

    I have heard that the true immortals of the upper realms
    Love purity above all—breathing in starlight, refusing waste,
    Feasting on clouds and jade to extend their years,
    Washing their marrow, cutting their hair to preserve eternal youth.
    If I too possess such virtue in this world,
    Why should I compete with withered age for longevity?

    Have you not heard of Lu Tong, who in hunger
    Played with three hundred poems? While the five thousand words
    Of the Tao Te Ching are but endless scribbling in the void.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Lu Tong was a renowned Tang poet known for his obsession with tea and poetry; his 'Ten Rhapsodies on Tea' celebrate the spiritual dimensions of tea drinking.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to the five thousand words alludes to the Tao Te Ching, suggesting that wordless experience transcends all written wisdom.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'true immortals' and their practices reflect Daoist immortality traditions, which the poet playfully contrasts with the simple spiritual elevation achieved through tea meditation.
